## Idea

An _$(\infty,n)$-category of spans_ in [[âˆž-groupoid]] is an [[(âˆž,n)-category]] whose

* [[object]]s are [[âˆž-groupoid]]s;

* [[morphism]]s $X \to Y$ are [[span]]s 

  $$
    \array{
      && Z
      \\
      & \swarrow && \searrow
      \\
      X &&&& Y
    }
  $$

  in [[âˆžGrpd]]

* [[2-morphism]]s are spans of spans

  $$
    \array{
      && Z
      \\
      & \swarrow &\uparrow& \searrow
      \\
      X &&Q&& Y
      \\
      & \nwarrow &\downarrow& \nearrow
      \\
      && Z'
    }
  $$

  (where the triangular sub-[[diagram]]s are filled with [[2-morphism]]s in [[âˆžGrpd]] which we do not display here)

* and so on up to [[k-morphism|n-morphism]]s

* $k \gt n$-morphisms are equivalences of order $(k-n)$ of higher spans.

Using the symmetric monoidal structure on [[âˆžGrpd]] this becomes a [[symmetric monoidal (âˆž,n)-category]].

More generally, for $C$ some [[symmetric monoidal (âˆž,n)-category]], there is a symmetric monoidal $(\infty,n)$-category of spans over $C$, whose

* [[object]]s are [[âˆž-groupoid]]s $X$ equipped with an [[(âˆž,n)-functor]] $X \to C$;

* [[morphism]]s $X \to Y$ are [[span]]s in [[(âˆž,1)Cat]] over $C$

  $$
    \array{
      && Z
      \\
      & \swarrow && \searrow
      \\
      X &&\swArrow&& Y
      \\
      & \searrow && \swarrow
      \\
      && C
    }
  $$

* and so on.

Even more generally one can allow the [[âˆž-groupoid]]s $X, Y, \cdots$ to be [[(âˆž,n)-categories]] themselves.

## Definition
 {#Definition}

### Direct definition

The [[(âˆž,2)-category]] of spans in [[âˆžGrpd]] is discussed in some detail in ([Dyckerhoff-Kapranov 12, section 10](#DyckerhoffKapranov12)).
For a sketch of the definition for all $n$ see ([Lurie, page 57](#Lurie)).

### Definition via coalgebras
 {#DefinitionViaCoalgebras}

In ([BenZvi-Nadler 13, remark 1.17](#BenZviNadler13)) it is observed that 

$$
  Span_n(\mathbf{H}) \simeq E_n Alg_b(\mathbf{H}^{op})
$$

is equivalently the [[(âˆž,n)-category]] of [[En-algebras]] and [[(âˆž,1)-bimodules]] between them in the [[opposite (âˆž,1)-category]] of $\mathbf{H}$ (since every object in a cartesian category is uniquely a [[coalgebra]] by its [[diagonal]] map).

(This immediately applies that every object in $Span_n(\mathbf{H})$ is a self-[[fully dualizable object]].)

To see how this works, consider $X \in \mathbf{H}$ any object regarded as a coalgebra in $\mathbf{H}$ via its [[diagonal map]]. Then a [[comodule]] $E$ over it is a [[co-action]]

$$
  E \to E \times X
$$

and hence is canoncially given by just a map $E \to X$. 

Then for 

$$
  \array{
    && E_1 &&&& E_2
    \\
    & \swarrow && \searrow && \swarrow && \searrow
    \\
    X && && Y && && Z
  }
$$

two consecutive spans, now interpreted as two bi-comodules, their [[tensor product]] of comodules over $Y$ as a coalgebra is the limit over

$$
  E_1 \times E_2
  \stackrel{\to}{\to}
  E_1 \times X \times E_2
  \stackrel{\to}{\stackrel{\to}{\to}}
  ...
$$

This is indeed the fiber product

$$
  E_1 \underset{X}{\times} E_2 \stackrel{(p_1, p_2)}{\to} E_1 \times E_2
$$

as it should be for the composition of [[correspondences]].

## Properties
 {#Properties}

+-- {: .num_prop }
###### Claim

$Span_n(\infty Grpd)$ is a [[symmetric monoidal (âˆž,n)-category]] [[cobordism hypothesis|with duals]].

More generally If $C$ is any symmetric monoidal $(\infty,n)$-category with 
duals, then so is $Span_n(\infty Grpd,C)$.

=--

This appears as ([Lurie, remark 3.2.3](#Lurie)).

Let $Bord_n$ be the [[(âˆž,n)-category of cobordisms]].

+-- {: .num_prop #HomsFromBordIntoSpan}
###### Claim

The following data are equivalent

1. Symmetric monoidal $(\infty,n)$-functors

   $$
     Bord_n \to Span_n(\infty Grpd)
   $$

1. Pairs $(X,V)$, where $X$ is a [[topological space]] and $V \to X$ a [[vector bundle]] of [[rank]] $n$.

=--

This appears as ([Lurie, claim 3.2.4](#Lurie)).

+-- {: .num_note }
###### Note

In view of the [[cobordism hypothesis]] for <a href="http://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/cobordism+hypothesis#CobsWithExtraTopStructure">cobordisms equipped with extra topological structure</a> and noticing that

$$
  Bord_n \simeq Bord_n^{O(n)}
$$

([Lurie, example 2.4.22](#Lurie)) this says something like that in $Span_n(\infty Grpd)$ every object of [[âˆžGrpd]] becomes fully dualizable.

=--

